[`state`][1] and [`props`][2] need to be considered as **immutable**.

In your case, mutating the `someArrayProp` directly without making a new instance, will **not cause** a render.

```
class App extends React.Component {
  render() {
    const { jsonObject } = this.state;

    // Some logic changing `jsonObject` like:
    jsonObject.prop3.anotherprop.someanotherprop2.someArrayProp = [&#39;hello&#39;];


    return &lt;MyPureComponent layout={jsonObject} /&gt;;
  }
}
```

In the above case, while `MyPureComponent` is a `PureComponent`, the `shallow comparison` will compare the references which are the same.

```
class MyPureComponent extends PureComponent {

  /* PureComponent implements shallow comparison by default

  shouldComponentUpdate(nextProps) {
     return this.props.layout !== next.props.layout;
  }

  */

  render() {}
}
```

That why [the best practice is not mutating data][3].

```
class App extends React.Component {
  render() {
    const { jsonObject } = this.state;

    // Some logic changing deep nested entry
    const someArrayChanged = ...;

    return &lt;MyPureComponent layout={{ ...jsonObject, ...someArrayChanged }} /&gt;;
  }
}
```

&gt; Should I really worry about this and implement my own `componentShouldUpdate` function to check differences? Or should I create separate props based on my deeply nested JSON to overcome this issue?

The answer depends on how you mutate the data, if directly - you should implement your own `componentShouldUpdate`, else, you don&#39;t need to worry.

In general, `componentShouldUpdate` is used when a component makes unnecessary renders due to failure of the default `shallow comparison`.

  [1]: https://reactjs.org/docs/react-component.html#state
  [2]: https://reactjs.org/docs/react-component.html#props
  [3]: https://reactjs.org/docs/optimizing-performance.html#the-power-of-not-mutating-data

